00:06:34.450 --> 00:06:37.570
It can be a business
type behavior,

00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:39.430
like getting your
employees to take

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:41.870
better care of their health.

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:44.320
Make sure to write it down,
because toward the end,

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:47.300
I'm going to call on some of
you to talk about your behavior.

00:06:47.300 --> 00:06:49.790
And we'll call someone
up here, actually.

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:56.600
All right, how many of you
have had the situation where

00:06:56.600 --> 00:07:00.680
you are trying to get something
out, you're trying to talk,

00:07:00.680 --> 00:07:03.720
and someone keeps
interrupting you?

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:05.750
I think probably all of us have.

00:07:05.750 --> 00:07:08.120
Yep, all of us have
experienced that.

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:10.790
Now how many of you
get frustrated when

00:07:10.790 --> 00:07:15.510
you're trying to talk, and the
person keeps frustrating you?

00:07:15.510 --> 00:07:19.290
Well, it may not be
that person's fault.

00:07:19.290 --> 00:07:26.190
So that person may be doing what
I call an automatic behavior.

00:07:26.190 --> 00:07:28.650
So an automatic behavior is
something where we're not

00:07:28.650 --> 00:07:31.020
even aware of what we're doing.

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:34.340
It just happens unconsciously.

00:07:34.340 --> 00:07:38.300
And knowing that something
is an automatic behavior

00:07:38.300 --> 00:07:41.130
allows us to know
how to address it.

00:07:41.130 --> 00:07:44.360
So other examples of
an automatic behavior

00:07:44.360 --> 00:07:48.650
are forgetting that we're
not standing up straight,

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:50.960
eating food that's just
sitting in front of us

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:53.780
without even being aware
of what we're doing.

00:07:53.780 --> 00:07:55.520
Those are automatic behaviors.

00:07:55.520 --> 00:07:57.040
But once we know
that something's

00:07:57.040 --> 00:08:00.860
an automatic behavior, there are
a set of tools and strategies

00:08:00.860 --> 00:08:03.904
that we can use to change it.

00:08:03.904 --> 00:08:05.320
But before we get
into that, let's

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:07.270
talk about the second
type of behavior.

00:08:10.700 --> 00:08:15.580
So while waiting at a
stoplight to cross the street,

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:22.160
I'd often pull out my phone,
check email to burn some time.

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:25.400
And sometimes, I'd
even cross the street

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:28.640
while I'm still
reading the email.

00:08:28.640 --> 00:08:30.750
That's not always the best idea.

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:33.169
It can lead to accidents.

00:08:33.169 --> 00:08:35.870
It can lead me tripping in
the middle of the street.

00:08:35.870 --> 00:08:37.549
I shouldn't be doing that.

00:08:37.549 --> 00:08:43.250
But I feel like I
wasn't able to stop.

00:08:43.250 --> 00:08:45.770
I felt like I had to just
finish reading this email,

00:08:45.770 --> 00:08:47.510
and then I'll put
the phone away.

00:08:47.510 --> 00:08:53.320
So this is an example of what
I call a burning behavior.

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:54.890
While automatic
behaviors are things

00:08:54.890 --> 00:08:57.890
that happen unconsciously,
automatically,

00:08:57.890 --> 00:09:01.100
burning behaviors
are behaviors where

00:09:01.100 --> 00:09:06.200
we're aware of what we're doing,
but we feel powerless to stop.

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:09.870
We feel like we just can't stop.

00:09:09.870 --> 00:09:14.420
So in my case, knowing that
it was a burning behavior,

00:09:14.420 --> 00:09:16.140
I was able to stop it.

00:09:16.140 --> 00:09:19.490
And part of that solution
comes from, every week now,

00:09:19.490 --> 00:09:22.220
I take a digital day of rest.

00:09:22.220 --> 00:09:26.660
So from Friday to Saturday,
I don't use any apps.

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:28.850
I don't check email.

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:30.290
I don't even talk about work.

00:09:30.290 --> 00:09:33.930
It's just time for
friends and family.

00:09:33.930 --> 00:09:39.390
And I was able to
address that and to stop

00:09:39.390 --> 00:09:43.410
what could be a growing digital
addiction, because I knew

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:46.090
this was a burning behavior.

00:09:46.090 --> 00:09:47.880
But before we get
into that, let me

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:51.480
tell you about the
last type of behavior

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:58.460
and also go into the background
of how I came to study this.

00:09:58.460 --> 00:10:00.660
So this is my brother up here.

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:03.970
And when I was in
graduate school,

00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:07.250
just down the street
here at Stanford,

00:10:07.250 --> 00:10:09.430
my brother came up to visit.

00:10:09.430 --> 00:10:13.360
Now he had been suffering from
an intestinal disorder called

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:15.420
Crohn's disease.

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:19.830
And he came up to visit, and
he was just in too much pain

00:10:19.830 --> 00:10:22.110
to go back home.

00:10:22.110 --> 00:10:25.390
So we brought him to
the emergency room.

00:10:25.390 --> 00:10:28.150
And they looked at
him, and it turns out

00:10:28.150 --> 00:10:31.440
his intestines had burst.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:34.860
So he was rushed into
emergency surgery,

00:10:34.860 --> 00:10:38.500
and they saved his life.

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:40.300
He was minutes away
from dying, they said.

00:10:40.300 --> 00:10:42.620
They saved his life.

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:46.690
So he spent two weeks
recovering at Stanford Hospital.

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:48.930
Then he was prescribed
daily medication,

00:10:48.930 --> 00:10:55.450
advised to change his lifestyle,
and then he was released.

00:10:55.450 --> 00:10:57.940
Now try to put yourself in my
brother's situation the way

00:10:57.940 --> 00:10:59.860
that I did.

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:04.260
You just almost
died, and you've been

00:11:04.260 --> 00:11:07.155
told, change your lifestyle.

00:11:07.155 --> 00:11:12.020
Now how likely do you guys
think you would be to do that?

00:11:12.020 --> 00:11:14.270
If you're like my brother,
if you're like most people,

00:11:14.270 --> 00:11:16.910
you'd say, I'm going to change.

00:11:16.910 --> 00:11:18.830
I'm going to eat differently.

00:11:18.830 --> 00:11:20.047
I'm going to exercise.

00:11:20.047 --> 00:11:21.380
I'm going to take my medication.

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:25.160
I'm going to do everything
that I'm supposed to do.

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:27.688
And my brother said
he'd do that 100%.

00:11:27.688 --> 00:11:29.185
But he didn't.

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:34.000
I didn't understand why.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:40.710
I-- my family and I
were really close.

00:11:40.710 --> 00:11:42.370
I love my brother.

00:11:42.370 --> 00:11:48.260
So I was on the phone with
my mom for hours every day.

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:50.350
And we were trying
to figure out,

00:11:50.350 --> 00:11:56.610
what could we do to get him to
follow these recommendations?

00:11:56.610 --> 00:11:58.700
Why wasn't he doing it?

00:11:58.700 --> 00:12:00.230
I was scared for him.

00:12:00.230 --> 00:12:01.940
I was worried.

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:03.740
I was confused.

00:12:03.740 --> 00:12:04.890
And I was frustrated.

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:06.680
And so I started
searching for answers.

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:09.980
I started talking to all
different types of people,

00:12:09.980 --> 00:12:13.880
experts in education, in
medicine, in business,

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:16.400
and I was trying
to find answers.

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:22.030
But I kept finding the same
one size fits all solution

00:12:22.030 --> 00:12:22.645
and answers.

00:12:25.180 --> 00:12:29.330
People were saying he needed
to have more willpower.

00:12:29.330 --> 00:12:32.030
People were saying he needed to
be more educated about Crohn's

00:12:32.030 --> 00:12:34.250
and how to change it.

00:12:34.250 --> 00:12:38.312
They were saying that he
wasn't motivated enough

00:12:38.312 --> 00:12:39.020
about his health.

00:12:39.020 --> 00:12:41.720
But my brother's smart.

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:42.634
He's motivated.

00:12:42.634 --> 00:12:43.550
He's health conscious.

00:12:43.550 --> 00:12:44.900
He's educated.

00:12:44.900 --> 00:12:47.010
So these answers didn't
make sense to me.

00:12:47.010 --> 00:12:52.100
And so that's why I
started studying this area.

00:12:52.100 --> 00:12:54.740
And after 15 years
of studying it,

00:12:54.740 --> 00:12:57.390
I've come up with some answers.

00:12:57.390 --> 00:12:59.360
So what I figured
out is it's not

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:01.910
about a one size
fits all solution,

00:13:01.910 --> 00:13:04.640
and it's not about
blaming the individual.

00:13:04.640 --> 00:13:09.350
What we need to know is that
not all behaviors are the same.

00:13:09.350 --> 00:13:13.210
There are three
types of behaviors.

00:13:13.210 --> 00:13:18.230
While I was questioning why
my brother wasn't changing,

00:13:18.230 --> 00:13:21.320
other things were happening
at the same time in my life.

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:23.810
I was in a band and
trying to figure out,

00:13:23.810 --> 00:13:26.180
how do we get the
fans of our band

00:13:26.180 --> 00:13:29.720
to keep coming back to our
shows, to keep buying albums?

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:31.790
I was teaching
classes at Stanford

00:13:31.790 --> 00:13:36.140
and wondering, why was it that
the students in our classes

00:13:36.140 --> 00:13:39.020
would wait until the
day a paper was due,

00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:41.090
and then they'd
ask for more time?

00:13:41.090 --> 00:13:43.730
Or I was wondering,
how could I get myself,

00:13:43.730 --> 00:13:45.770
where I was working on
so many different things,

00:13:45.770 --> 00:13:50.090
to stay engaged and motivated
in doing all of them?

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:53.600
Now all these seem like
really different things,

00:13:53.600 --> 00:13:58.640
but if you look deeper,
they're actually

00:13:58.640 --> 00:14:00.800
united by one common thread.

00:14:00.800 --> 00:14:06.380
And that's, how do we get
people to stick with things?

00:14:06.380 --> 00:14:09.640
So people often
were even planning

00:14:09.640 --> 00:14:12.326
what they were going to do,
but they still kept failing.

00:14:12.326 --> 00:14:14.200
So how do we get people
to stick with things?

00:14:14.200 --> 00:14:18.020
Well, what I found
is that we need

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:22.110
to know the three
types of behaviors.

00:14:22.110 --> 00:14:24.740
So the three types
of behaviors are

00:14:24.740 --> 00:14:27.050
automatic, burning,
and common behaviors,

00:14:27.050 --> 00:14:29.880
or what I call the
ABCs of behavior.

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:32.300
So I'll do a quick
recap about that.

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:34.130
Automatic behaviors,
are behaviors

00:14:34.130 --> 00:14:40.570
that happen unconsciously, like
the example of the interrupter.

00:14:40.570 --> 00:14:43.870
Burning behaviors,
burning behaviors.

00:14:43.870 --> 00:14:48.230
are behaviors that are not
happening unconsciously,

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:50.110
but we feel powerless to stop.

00:14:50.110 --> 00:14:54.090
Addictions are often
burning behaviors.

00:14:54.090 --> 00:14:57.750
And then third are
common behaviors.

00:14:57.750 --> 00:15:01.890
Common behaviors are the
most common of all behaviors.

00:15:01.890 --> 00:15:05.320
Common behaviors are
often due to motivation.

00:15:05.320 --> 00:15:08.580
So a common behavior
is something

00:15:08.580 --> 00:15:13.360
where we're aware
of what we're doing,

00:15:13.360 --> 00:15:17.500
but the risks of doing
it, or the energy

00:15:17.500 --> 00:15:21.730
that it takes for us to do
it, isn't worth the benefits

00:15:21.730 --> 00:15:23.980
we think we might
get from doing it.

00:15:23.980 --> 00:15:25.210
So let me say that again.

00:15:25.210 --> 00:15:26.110
I'll repeat that.

00:15:26.110 --> 00:15:28.330
Common behavior
is something where

00:15:28.330 --> 00:15:30.610
the energy that it takes
for us to do something,

00:15:30.610 --> 00:15:33.580
or the risk that it
takes for us to do it,

00:15:33.580 --> 00:15:37.680
isn't worth the benefit we think
we might get from doing it.

00:15:37.680 --> 00:15:40.750
So let me give an example,
because that's a lot.

00:15:40.750 --> 00:15:44.140
So my brothers lifestyle
change was an example

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:46.860
of a common behavior.

00:15:46.860 --> 00:15:51.030
Because despite being told that
he should change his lifestyle,

00:15:51.030 --> 00:15:54.790
and that may keep him out of
the hospital, he didn't think

00:15:54.790 --> 00:15:57.600
it was worth it to change.

00:15:57.600 --> 00:16:02.550
Why should he give up
things that he loved doing?

00:16:02.550 --> 00:16:04.560
Why should he change
the way he eats?

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:08.730
Why should he exercise more,
meditate, take medication?

00:16:08.730 --> 00:16:11.190
Why should he do these
things if there wasn't even

00:16:11.190 --> 00:16:14.550
a guarantee that it would work?

00:16:14.550 --> 00:16:17.420
That's a common behavior.

00:16:17.420 --> 00:16:22.670
But knowing that something is
a common behavior, or an A or B

00:16:22.670 --> 00:16:25.460
behavior, allows us
to know how to fix it.

00:16:25.460 --> 00:16:27.740
We just need to know
the set of tools

00:16:27.740 --> 00:16:29.600
for fixing those
types of behaviors.

00:16:33.040 --> 00:16:34.830
So the set of tools
are what I call

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:36.780
the forces of behavior change.

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:41.970
Now you guys may have
learned in physics that there

00:16:41.970 --> 00:16:44.370
are forces that move objects--

00:16:44.370 --> 00:16:48.080
that move objects--
can't move this.

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:52.110
There are forces that move
objects in certain directions.

00:16:52.110 --> 00:16:56.310
Well, there are behavioral
forces that move people.

00:16:56.310 --> 00:16:58.410
They get us to behave
in certain ways.

00:17:01.060 --> 00:17:06.690
Now just as a flight crew, or
a pilot, or aerospace engineers

00:17:06.690 --> 00:17:09.869
need to know the physical forces
that move a plane in order

00:17:09.869 --> 00:17:14.040
to fly it safely, all of us need
to know the behavioral forces

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:17.819
that move people so we can
behave the way we want.

00:17:17.819 --> 00:17:19.169
There are seven of these forces.

00:17:21.920 --> 00:17:25.540
So what I did, I came up with
a framework called SCIENCE,

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:29.890
where each one of the
letters of SCIENCE

00:17:29.890 --> 00:17:32.360
represents a different
one of the seven forces.

00:17:32.360 --> 00:17:36.010
And it's called
SCIENCE, not because you

00:17:36.010 --> 00:17:39.130
need a scientist to know it, but
because it's based on decades

00:17:39.130 --> 00:17:41.460
of scientific research.

00:17:41.460 --> 00:17:47.090
So S stands for "Stepladders."

00:17:47.090 --> 00:17:50.210
We know we're supposed to
do things in small steps,

00:17:50.210 --> 00:17:52.250
but we often don't.

00:17:52.250 --> 00:17:56.480
We often don't plan small
steps to change our behavior.

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:59.540
A few weeks ago, I ran
into someone at the market.

00:17:59.540 --> 00:18:02.870
And he was a cross-country
runner in high school.

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:06.200
And he decided that he
wanted to run a marathon.

00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:10.010
He ran cross-country in high
school, so he knew how to run,

00:18:10.010 --> 00:18:11.680
but he hadn't run since then.

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:13.389
It had been 20 years since then.

00:18:13.389 --> 00:18:15.680
And he decides, I'm just
going to go run this marathon,

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:16.638
and I'm going to do it.

00:18:16.638 --> 00:18:17.937
I've got the motivation.

00:18:17.937 --> 00:18:18.770
I've got the energy.

00:18:18.770 --> 00:18:20.090
I can do this.

00:18:20.090 --> 00:18:22.250
And he actually did pretty well.

00:18:22.250 --> 00:18:25.600
He got to mile 19,
but then he collapsed.

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:28.040
And he said, I didn't
finish that marathon,

00:18:28.040 --> 00:18:32.810
and I'm probably not going to
run another marathon again.

00:18:32.810 --> 00:18:35.360
Now that story, I don't
know about for you guys,

00:18:35.360 --> 00:18:39.260
but there's no way I could run
a marathon without training

00:18:39.260 --> 00:18:40.460
for it.

00:18:40.460 --> 00:18:42.800
So this makes a lot of sense.

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:45.020
If we want to be
able to do something,

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:46.940
if we want to
stick to things, we

00:18:46.940 --> 00:18:51.080
need to start in small,
incremental steps.

00:18:51.080 --> 00:18:53.190
But just like the
marathon example,

00:18:53.190 --> 00:18:56.120
we often make the same
mistakes in our own life.

00:18:56.120 --> 00:19:00.590
If we want to be able to
make a New Year's resolution

00:19:00.590 --> 00:19:04.370
to go to the gym, we'll say,
I'm going to go to the gym.

00:19:04.370 --> 00:19:07.040
I haven't really been at
all before this past year,

00:19:07.040 --> 00:19:10.400
but I'm going to go five days
a week for the next year.

00:19:10.400 --> 00:19:12.900
And that's a pretty tall order.

00:19:12.900 --> 00:19:16.040
So we need to think about
things in small steps.

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:19.400
But the question is, how do
you know what a small step is?

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:24.600
How do you know how
small a step should be?

00:19:24.600 --> 00:19:28.760
So I created this figure
here called Steps, Goals,

00:19:28.760 --> 00:19:29.350
and Dreams.

00:19:32.510 --> 00:19:35.600
The marathon example, if I was
going to try to run a marathon,

00:19:35.600 --> 00:19:38.660
I've never run one
before, I'm not going

00:19:38.660 --> 00:19:40.010
to be able to do it in a week.

00:19:40.010 --> 00:19:42.575
I'm not going to be able to
do it in a month, probably.

00:19:42.575 --> 00:19:44.750
It'll probably take
me a few months

00:19:44.750 --> 00:19:46.260
of training to run a marathon.

00:19:46.260 --> 00:19:48.770
So that's what I call a dream.

00:19:48.770 --> 00:19:54.170
It's attainable, but it
takes some time to get there.

00:19:54.170 --> 00:19:59.060
If I want something
now to do, a first step

00:19:59.060 --> 00:20:01.460
would be something that
takes less than a week.

00:20:01.460 --> 00:20:05.360
So getting a pair of running
shoes may be a first step.

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:08.790
Or if I haven't run before
much, running for 10,

00:20:08.790 --> 00:20:12.010
15, 20 minutes, just something
small would be a first step.

00:20:12.010 --> 00:20:12.510
So.

00:20:12.510 --> 00:20:15.770
this figure will
teach us how we can

00:20:15.770 --> 00:20:19.040
plan steps that are the right
size so that we don't give up.

00:20:24.220 --> 00:20:25.850
So that's Stepladders.

00:20:25.850 --> 00:20:28.640
C stands for "Community."

00:20:28.640 --> 00:20:30.710
We all want to be
different from the crowd.

00:20:30.710 --> 00:20:32.870
We want to be different
than other individuals.

00:20:32.870 --> 00:20:36.060
But our social
environment matters.

00:20:36.060 --> 00:20:39.080
It matters a lot more than
we even think it does.

00:20:39.080 --> 00:20:41.270
And there's a science
how to leverage

00:20:41.270 --> 00:20:43.535
social to create change.

00:20:46.110 --> 00:20:48.750
One of the studies that
we do in our research--

00:20:48.750 --> 00:20:52.350
I created what's called
the Hope Intervention.

00:20:52.350 --> 00:20:55.200
Hope Intervention is
an online community

00:20:55.200 --> 00:20:57.870
where it's designed
to motivate people

00:20:57.870 --> 00:20:59.940
to change their behavior.

00:20:59.940 --> 00:21:02.870
We invite people to a
12-week intervention.

00:21:02.870 --> 00:21:06.630
And we have found that
these interventions

00:21:06.630 --> 00:21:10.230
to change people's behavior
across different areas--

00:21:10.230 --> 00:21:14.130
drug use, HIV, different
types of behaviors--

00:21:14.130 --> 00:21:16.470
we find that within 12
weeks, we can get people

00:21:16.470 --> 00:21:18.650
to change their behavior.

00:21:18.650 --> 00:21:22.320
And it leverages the
force of community

00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:26.040
through these
online communities.

00:21:26.040 --> 00:21:28.740
We find that people in
our Hope Interventions

00:21:28.740 --> 00:21:31.140
are about two to three
times as likely to change

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:33.650
their behavior.

00:21:33.650 --> 00:21:36.980
Now I stands for "Important."

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:39.590
People won't do things
unless they want to do it,

00:21:39.590 --> 00:21:42.700
unless they're motivated, right?

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:46.150
Yes, but no, not necessarily.

00:21:46.150 --> 00:21:48.280
Motivation definitely
matters, and that's

00:21:48.280 --> 00:21:50.800
why it's up here as one
of these seven forces.

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:54.610
But people actually don't
need to be motivated

00:21:54.610 --> 00:21:57.780
in order to stick with things.

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:01.290
So I'll give an example
from the Hope Intervention

00:22:01.290 --> 00:22:02.890
that I was mentioning.

00:22:02.890 --> 00:22:06.150
We did a Hope
Intervention on trying

00:22:06.150 --> 00:22:11.280
to get people at high risk
for HIV to get an HIV test.

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:14.070
They weren't interested
in getting an HIV test.

00:22:14.070 --> 00:22:17.640
We had them sign
up for our group.

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:19.320
They took a survey.

00:22:19.320 --> 00:22:20.580
We paid them to take a survey.

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:22.788
And then we said, all right,
you guys are free to go.

00:22:22.788 --> 00:22:25.500
You don't need to be in
this community anymore.

00:22:25.500 --> 00:22:29.340
It was up to us to keep them
engaged, keep them motivated.

00:22:29.340 --> 00:22:35.320
Well, by the end of the study,
people in our Hope group

00:22:35.320 --> 00:22:38.830
were much more likely, two
to three times as likely,

00:22:38.830 --> 00:22:42.070
as people who weren't
to test for HIV.

00:22:42.070 --> 00:22:46.180
They still weren't interested,
necessarily, in testing,

00:22:46.180 --> 00:22:47.800
but we got them to test.

00:22:47.800 --> 00:22:52.540
So the point is important
and motivation matters,

00:22:52.540 --> 00:22:54.720
but if we're using
the other forces,

00:22:54.720 --> 00:22:56.440
we can often get
people to do things,

00:22:56.440 --> 00:22:59.625
even if they're not motivated
to do that thing themselves.

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:06.070
Now E stands for "Easy."

00:23:06.070 --> 00:23:08.920
If we can make something
easier for people

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:11.650
to do than for
them not to do it,

00:23:11.650 --> 00:23:14.900
or easier for ourselves
to do than to not do,

00:23:14.900 --> 00:23:16.230
people will do it.

00:23:16.230 --> 00:23:16.960
It's that simple.

00:23:19.670 --> 00:23:26.650
Just like we can get
people to do easy things

00:23:26.650 --> 00:23:29.470
by changing around
our environment,

00:23:29.470 --> 00:23:31.270
we can do that with behaviors.

00:23:31.270 --> 00:23:36.850
In this chapter on easy, I talk
about some business examples

00:23:36.850 --> 00:23:40.360
of how businesses were
able to make things easy.

00:23:40.360 --> 00:23:44.300
So who's heard the
story of Joe Coulombe?

00:23:48.210 --> 00:23:53.450
So if you guys ask someone
about the story of--

00:23:53.450 --> 00:23:57.140
let's see, what time is it?

00:23:57.140 --> 00:23:57.932
OK, we've got time.

00:23:57.932 --> 00:23:59.056
Let me tell you this story.

00:23:59.056 --> 00:23:59.900
It's a good story.

00:23:59.900 --> 00:24:05.330
So Joe Coulombe-- and
this took place in 1958,

00:24:05.330 --> 00:24:07.070
in the late 1950s--

00:24:07.070 --> 00:24:09.830
he had graduated from
Stanford School of Business,

00:24:09.830 --> 00:24:11.300
from the GSB.

00:24:11.300 --> 00:24:15.150
And he went to go work for
a company called Owl Rexall.

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:19.340
Owl Rexall was a grocery
chain, grocery store chain.

00:24:19.340 --> 00:24:21.590
And what they told
him is, hey, Joe,

00:24:21.590 --> 00:24:23.330
we want you to go
off on your own

00:24:23.330 --> 00:24:27.320
and start this new chain
of stores called Pronto.

00:24:27.320 --> 00:24:29.030
So he starts Pronto.

00:24:29.030 --> 00:24:30.620
But Pronto is struggling.

00:24:30.620 --> 00:24:32.420
He wasn't doing well.

00:24:32.420 --> 00:24:36.590
The reason is there was this
other competitor grocery

00:24:36.590 --> 00:24:38.450
store that had just
come out, and they

00:24:38.450 --> 00:24:39.730
were doing really well.

00:24:39.730 --> 00:24:42.350
They were called 7-Eleven.

00:24:42.350 --> 00:24:45.550
So 7-Eleven was open
at unprecedented hours.

00:24:45.550 --> 00:24:48.470
They were open 7:00
AM to 11:00 PM.

00:24:48.470 --> 00:24:51.480
They were offering
all kinds of products.

00:24:51.480 --> 00:24:53.330
Joe and Pronto couldn't compete.

00:24:53.330 --> 00:24:56.900
So Owl Rexall said,
it's not working.

00:24:56.900 --> 00:25:01.960
Let's axe Pronto, and we'll
do something else, Joe.

00:25:01.960 --> 00:25:04.100
But Joe didn't want to do that.

00:25:04.100 --> 00:25:09.650
He left work from Owl Rexall,
and he mortgaged his house,

00:25:09.650 --> 00:25:13.750
and decides he's going to go
on his own and save Pronto.

00:25:13.750 --> 00:25:15.590
But he didn't know how to do it.

00:25:15.590 --> 00:25:18.650
So he says, OK, I'm going to
take a vacation, meanwhile.

00:25:18.650 --> 00:25:22.250
I'm going to go to the
Caribbean and think this over.

00:25:22.250 --> 00:25:25.650
While he's in the
Caribbean, he's relaxing,

00:25:25.650 --> 00:25:27.440
he's laying by the beach.

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:29.090
People are bringing
him Mai Tais.

00:25:29.090 --> 00:25:30.410
He's drinking.

00:25:30.410 --> 00:25:31.970
They're bringing him food.

00:25:31.970 --> 00:25:36.350
He's listening to calypso
and reggae music there.

00:25:36.350 --> 00:25:40.640
And he realizes, this is a
pretty sweet setup for someone

00:25:40.640 --> 00:25:42.020
who's on vacation.

00:25:42.020 --> 00:25:45.300
They're making it pretty
easy for tourists to be here.

00:25:45.300 --> 00:25:48.950
Maybe there's something that
I can do with this lifestyle,

00:25:48.950 --> 00:25:52.480
with this making it easy, and I
can bring this back to Pronto.

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:54.190
So that's what he does.

00:25:54.190 --> 00:25:55.510
So he goes back home.

00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:58.540
And compared to
competitor stores,

00:25:58.540 --> 00:26:03.250
which were offering 10
different types of mayonnaise,

00:26:03.250 --> 00:26:07.750
13 types of bread, a ton of
different product choices, Joe

00:26:07.750 --> 00:26:09.961
decides, I'm going
to have just one.

00:26:09.961 --> 00:26:12.460
I'm going to make it easy for
people when they come in here.

00:26:12.460 --> 00:26:14.720
They're going to know
what they can purchase.

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:15.970
And it worked.

00:26:15.970 --> 00:26:16.690
It worked.

00:26:16.690 --> 00:26:19.810
People started not only
coming into his stores,

00:26:19.810 --> 00:26:23.170
but they kept on buying,
and it kept on working.

00:26:23.170 --> 00:26:26.080
And Pronto stores, which
ultimately changed their name,

00:26:26.080 --> 00:26:27.790
became a huge lasting success.

00:26:27.790 --> 00:26:30.090
They're still around today.

00:26:30.090 --> 00:26:35.591
Anyone have an idea of
what the store chain is?

00:26:35.591 --> 00:26:36.090
You got it.

00:26:36.090 --> 00:26:37.440
Say it louder.

00:26:37.440 --> 00:26:38.550
Trader Joe's.

00:26:38.550 --> 00:26:39.120
Exactly.

00:26:39.120 --> 00:26:42.327
So his name was Joe,
they're inspired by the trip

00:26:42.327 --> 00:26:43.035
to the Caribbean.

00:26:43.035 --> 00:26:45.940
So now, when you see
the Hawaiian shirts,

00:26:45.940 --> 00:26:47.960
it's from the story of Joe.

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:50.610
Now Trader Joe's
isn't the only one

00:26:50.610 --> 00:26:53.470
to leverage this force of easy.

00:26:53.470 --> 00:26:55.670
Think about Amazon.

00:26:55.670 --> 00:27:00.600
Amazon Prime, Amazon
Dash, makes shopping easy.

00:27:00.600 --> 00:27:03.885
You don't have to
leave your home.

00:27:03.885 --> 00:27:05.970
I don't go shopping
anywhere anymore,

00:27:05.970 --> 00:27:07.830
just everything on Amazon.

00:27:07.830 --> 00:27:09.990
They can deliver to
you before you even

00:27:09.990 --> 00:27:11.790
know what you want to order.

00:27:11.790 --> 00:27:13.380
That's pretty easy.

00:27:13.380 --> 00:27:16.240
Google, you guys have
actually done it too.

00:27:16.240 --> 00:27:17.770
And with some of
you in the group,

00:27:17.770 --> 00:27:20.670
you may have been
involved in this.

00:27:20.670 --> 00:27:25.620
So Google, as you guys know,
one of the founding tenets,

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:27.210
one of the benefits
of Google, is

00:27:27.210 --> 00:27:29.820
that there's food everywhere.

00:27:29.820 --> 00:27:35.760
Well, that also can lead to
the Google 15 or the Google 20.

00:27:35.760 --> 00:27:40.900
And so Google found that their
employees were not as healthy

00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:42.720
as they would like.

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:46.070
So they decided, we're going to
change around the dining halls,

00:27:46.070 --> 00:27:49.460
and make it so that we're going
to take the unhealthier foods

00:27:49.460 --> 00:27:52.850
and put it in the back and
make them in containers

00:27:52.850 --> 00:27:55.330
that aren't clear anymore.

00:27:55.330 --> 00:27:57.280
Had a big effect on
employee behavior,

00:27:57.280 --> 00:27:59.710
and on health, and on eating.

00:27:59.710 --> 00:28:02.770
So the force of easy
is a powerful way

00:28:02.770 --> 00:28:05.960
to change people's behavior.

00:28:05.960 --> 00:28:08.516
Next, N stands for "Neurohacks."

00:28:08.516 --> 00:28:11.750
Neurohacks are quick
mental shortcuts

00:28:11.750 --> 00:28:14.270
that can get us to
change our behavior.

00:28:14.270 --> 00:28:18.350
So just like hitting
Control-Alt-Delete on a PC

00:28:18.350 --> 00:28:22.130
can allow us to use a
program that was jammed up

00:28:22.130 --> 00:28:26.420
or reset things, neurohacks
allow us to reset our brain,

00:28:26.420 --> 00:28:30.230
and allow us to think and
behave in ways that we

00:28:30.230 --> 00:28:32.490
couldn't before.

00:28:32.490 --> 00:28:33.990
I'll give an example
of a neurohack.

00:28:33.990 --> 00:28:37.380
In the chapter on
neurohacks, I mention a story

00:28:37.380 --> 00:28:39.810
by a man named Mauricio.

00:28:39.810 --> 00:28:43.860
So Mauricio was a designer.

00:28:43.860 --> 00:28:45.450
He was in a funk though.

00:28:45.450 --> 00:28:47.490
He had just gotten a divorce.

00:28:47.490 --> 00:28:50.500
He didn't feel motivated
to be a designer anymore.

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:52.230
He didn't feel
like going to work.

00:28:52.230 --> 00:28:54.330
But he didn't know what to do.

00:28:54.330 --> 00:28:56.850
But he got an idea while
he was at work one day.

00:28:56.850 --> 00:28:59.070
He came across the
familiar screen

00:28:59.070 --> 00:29:01.350
of it's flashing in
front of him, saying,

00:29:01.350 --> 00:29:03.390
you need to change
your password.

00:29:03.390 --> 00:29:07.660
And he says, I'm going to use
my password to change my life

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:08.999
and get me out of this funk.

00:29:08.999 --> 00:29:09.790
So what does he do?

00:29:09.790 --> 00:29:13.780
So he says, I'm going to change
my password to the number

00:29:13.780 --> 00:29:16.060
"4 get her."

00:29:16.060 --> 00:29:18.820
"4get her."

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:19.360
Forget her.

00:29:22.210 --> 00:29:23.760
Or sorry, not--

00:29:23.760 --> 00:29:25.770
"4give her."

00:29:25.770 --> 00:29:27.630
"4give her."

00:29:27.630 --> 00:29:29.220
So forgive her.

00:29:29.220 --> 00:29:34.490
So he decides, I'm going to,
every day, have to type "4give

00:29:34.490 --> 00:29:39.410
her," and that'll get me
to be able to forgive her

00:29:39.410 --> 00:29:41.670
for what's happened.

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:44.170
And when he first started doing
it, it was pretty difficult.

00:29:44.170 --> 00:29:46.480
You can imagine, he's
going through this divorce,

00:29:46.480 --> 00:29:50.460
he's having a tough time, and
now he has to type "4give her."

00:29:50.460 --> 00:29:52.980
So the first few times, it was
difficult. But what he found

00:29:52.980 --> 00:29:59.920
is that as he kept typing "4give
her," it became easier to do.

00:29:59.920 --> 00:30:03.210
He didn't have these
terrible feelings

00:30:03.210 --> 00:30:04.307
that he thought he would.

00:30:04.307 --> 00:30:06.640
He didn't have to change his
password to something else.

00:30:06.640 --> 00:30:09.120
He could continue doing this.

00:30:09.120 --> 00:30:12.240
And it just reset his
brain and made him think,

00:30:12.240 --> 00:30:14.260
I'm getting over her.

00:30:14.260 --> 00:30:15.240
I'm forgiving her.

00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:16.370
I'm forgetting.

00:30:16.370 --> 00:30:17.580
And I'm moving on.

00:30:17.580 --> 00:30:19.770
And he has moved on since.

00:30:19.770 --> 00:30:23.250
It was a neurohack that
allowed him to move on.

00:30:23.250 --> 00:30:25.450
But he didn't just stop there.

00:30:25.450 --> 00:30:29.670
He also was smoking, and
he changed his password

00:30:29.670 --> 00:30:31.610
to "quit smoking."

00:30:31.610 --> 00:30:35.730
And he told me that he
quit smoking overnight.

00:30:35.730 --> 00:30:39.670
Five years later, he
hasn't been smoking since.

00:30:39.670 --> 00:30:43.706
That's the power of neurohacks.

00:30:43.706 --> 00:30:47.670
C stands for "Captivating."

00:30:47.670 --> 00:30:51.100
We know that we should
reward ourselves,

00:30:51.100 --> 00:30:54.820
we should reward people
for doing things in order

00:30:54.820 --> 00:30:57.340
to create lasting change.

00:30:57.340 --> 00:30:59.680
But rewards don't always work.

00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:02.590
Think about the
gamification fad,

00:31:02.590 --> 00:31:05.320
which has kind of fizzled out.

00:31:05.320 --> 00:31:10.240
So rewards work, but not
always, because not all types

00:31:10.240 --> 00:31:11.980
of rewards work.

00:31:11.980 --> 00:31:15.040
Not everyone's motivated
by points, and badges,

00:31:15.040 --> 00:31:16.930
and leaderboards.

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:22.200
Now we need not just any
reward, but we need a reward

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:24.690
that's truly captivating.

00:31:24.690 --> 00:31:26.730
It's got to be
important to people.

00:31:26.730 --> 00:31:29.860
Different things are
motivating to different people.

00:31:29.860 --> 00:31:32.699
So this chapter will
talk about the history,

00:31:32.699 --> 00:31:34.240
and there's a long
history going back

00:31:34.240 --> 00:31:37.090
about 100 years, of
how to motivate change

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:38.770
and how to create rewards.

00:31:38.770 --> 00:31:41.710
This chapter will talk about it.

00:31:41.710 --> 00:31:45.540
Finally, "E" stands
for "Engrained."

00:31:45.540 --> 00:31:48.980
Barack Obama was
known for making

00:31:48.980 --> 00:31:52.070
a routine out of the
clothes that he wore,

00:31:52.070 --> 00:31:54.140
the food that he ate, so
that he could save time

00:31:54.140 --> 00:31:58.080
for making important
decisions about our country.

00:31:58.080 --> 00:32:04.890
Mark Zuckerberg, he has 20
versions of the same shirt.

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:08.730
Writer Ernest
Hemingway, he was known

00:32:08.730 --> 00:32:12.750
for writing every day at the
same time in the morning.

00:32:12.750 --> 00:32:16.390
If you make something a routine,
it becomes easier to do,

00:32:16.390 --> 00:32:20.450
and it gets engrained
in our brain.

00:32:20.450 --> 00:32:21.980
So those are the seven forces.

00:32:21.980 --> 00:32:25.280
That's the SCIENCE framework.

00:32:25.280 --> 00:32:27.730
And now, all need to do is--

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:34.460
now that we know the ABCs,
we know that three types

00:32:34.460 --> 00:32:37.750
of behaviors, and we
know the seven forces,

00:32:37.750 --> 00:32:42.230
we just need to know which
of the seven forces do we use

00:32:42.230 --> 00:32:42.730
and when.

00:32:45.660 --> 00:32:51.460
So I created a
simple 2-step model.

00:32:51.460 --> 00:32:52.720
It's pretty easy.

00:32:52.720 --> 00:32:56.140
Step one, identify
whether something

00:32:56.140 --> 00:32:59.340
is an A, B, or C behavior.

00:32:59.340 --> 00:33:03.360
And second, apply the
forces needed to change

00:33:03.360 --> 00:33:04.290
that type of behavior.

00:33:08.830 --> 00:33:13.540
So this is what I call the
Science of Lasting Change.

00:33:13.540 --> 00:33:16.400
And here's the figure.

00:33:16.400 --> 00:33:20.320
You can see that, first, there's
automatic behaviors, burning

00:33:20.320 --> 00:33:22.540
behaviors, and common behaviors.

00:33:22.540 --> 00:33:25.630
Automatic behaviors, we're
not aware of what we're doing,

00:33:25.630 --> 00:33:29.020
so there's no brain in
the stick figure's head.

00:33:29.020 --> 00:33:32.170
Burning behaviors, we're
a little bit more aware.

00:33:32.170 --> 00:33:35.860
And then common behaviors,
we're fully aware.

00:33:35.860 --> 00:33:38.560
And as you can see,
the seven forces

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:40.840
are listed down at the bottom.

00:33:40.840 --> 00:33:45.190
And the more stars next to
that force, the more important

00:33:45.190 --> 00:33:48.910
it is for changing
that type of behavior.

00:33:48.910 --> 00:33:53.650
In general, as we get more
complicated types of behaviors,

00:33:53.650 --> 00:33:58.180
as we get more aware of it,
we need a larger set of tools

00:33:58.180 --> 00:34:00.790
to change those
types of behaviors.

00:34:00.790 --> 00:34:02.740
We need more forces.

00:34:02.740 --> 00:34:09.310
Now this framework is something
that I've put together

00:34:09.310 --> 00:34:12.550
based on decades of
scientific research

00:34:12.550 --> 00:34:15.639
from other scientists,
and psychologists,

00:34:15.639 --> 00:34:17.790
and from our own work.

00:34:17.790 --> 00:34:22.310
I found that this works across
a number of different areas.

00:34:22.310 --> 00:34:23.940
We've used them in
the medical school.

00:34:23.940 --> 00:34:26.670
And we've used it and
applied it to people at risk

00:34:26.670 --> 00:34:29.250
for diseases where we
need to change health.

00:34:29.250 --> 00:34:31.260
I've found that it
works in my own life

00:34:31.260 --> 00:34:33.400
for personal behaviors.

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:36.810
And it works in business
work that I do too.

00:34:40.960 --> 00:34:44.260
So this gives you a
high level overview.

00:34:44.260 --> 00:34:48.460
And if there are more
questions, the book

00:34:48.460 --> 00:34:51.075
goes into a lot more detail
about this framework.

00:34:54.260 --> 00:34:57.320
But what I want to do now,
the purpose of this talk,

00:34:57.320 --> 00:35:00.400
I want to leave you guys with
understanding the difference

00:35:00.400 --> 00:35:03.050
between A, B, and C behaviors.

